indictis Latinis. The striae Latinae were not statae but concaptivae, i.e. were held at a time fixed each year by the con- suls, and proclaimed by a praeco. Until they had held this fes- tival on the Alban Meum, the consuls were not allowed to leave Rome (Liv. XXI. 63). The festival was made the occasion sor a general holiday, and was always accompanied by a iusti- tium, so that Philippus had no legal business to keep him in the city. Mommsen Hist. 1. 41—42.

77. impositus mannis, not ‘on horseback’, in which ease the plural (which some editors have explained as for uni ex mannis) would barely be justitiable; but in the carriage drawn by manni, as in Carm. 111. 27, 7. Orelli quotes Ov. Pont. 111. 4, 100 filius et iuncta, ut prius, ibit cquis, where however iunctis determines the meaning of the phrase more clearly: as in Verg. Aen.
